// The `prelude.env` sub-module: project-scoped environment access. These are host primitives — the
// runtime registers their implementations, bound to the project's `env_entries` store, when it boots (the
// pure built-ins in `prelude.ktr` need no such binding). They are called qualified as `env.get_secret`
// / `env.get_all`.
//
// The two readers realise the secret / non-secret split: a secret entry is read one key at a time through
// `get_secret`, whose result is a `string of private` (tainted secret — it must not cross a user-facing
// boundary such as a run result, only a sink like an http header / FFI call); the non-secret entries are
// read together through `get_all` as bare (public) strings.
//
// Errors: a missing secret is an anticipated configuration failure a program may want to fall back from
// (an optional integration, a default), so `get_secret` throws the typed `missing_secret` — catchable
// like any throw; uncaught, it still fails the run.

@"No secret env entry is set under @key@. Thrown by `get_secret` — catch it to fall back in-program
(`use handler { request throw(error: env.missing_secret) -> never { ... } }`)."
data missing_secret(key: string, message: string)

@"Read a secret env entry by key, returning its value as a private string (the value is tainted secret and
cannot flow to a user-facing boundary). A missing key throws `missing_secret` (carrying the key), so a
program can fall back for optional config; uncaught, the throw fails the run."
primitive agent get_secret(key: string) -> string of private with prelude.throw[missing_secret]

@"Read every non-secret env entry as a record of bare (public) strings, keyed by the env key."
primitive agent get_all() -> record[string]
